Adventure of Mountaineering
Climbing moun tains is called moun taineering. Those who climb moun tains for 
adventure are called moun taineer s. Every year, hundr eds of climber s, both men 
and women, climb the mos t difficult moun tains all around the world. India is 
famous for the Himala yas, the world's highes t moun tain range. World's highes t 
moun tain peak, Moun t Everest (8848m), which is in Nepal, also belong to the 
Himala yas. It attracts adventure seek ers from all over the world. People climb 
moun tains for the sake of adventure and also to explor e the things around. Scaling 
a moun tain peak also gives the sense of victory to a climber . 
Man y moun taineer s dream t of scaling Moun t Everest but it was Sir Edmund Hillar y 
of New Zealand and Sherpa Tenzing Norgay of Nepal who reached first to the top of 
peak on 29 May 1953. Later in 1984, Bachendri Pal was the first Indian woman to 
climb the Moun t Everest.
Bachendri Pal– The rough and tough woman Bachendri Pal was the first Indian 
woman and the fifth woman in the world to climb the Moun t Everest on 23 May 
1984. Prior to this, she also climbed the Gang otri and Rudr agaria peak s. India is 
proud of her. She has been awarded with the Padma Shri and Arjuna awards.

Key termsKey termsKey termsMoun taineering training– As we go higher up on the moun tains, the oxygen in the 
air becomes less. Ther efore, breathing gets difficult and the person feels tired. 
Ther e is also the problem of getting drinking water as the temper ature is very low 
at the higher altitudes. So, it is necessar y to under go training before going on a 
moun tain expedition. In our country, the Himala yan Moun taineering Institut e in 
Darjeeling and the Nehru Institut e of Moun taineering in Uttarkashi provide 
training to moun taineer s.
Climbing equipmen t– A moun taineer requir es ice-a xe, helme t, nylon ropes, 
aluminium ladder , oxygen cylinder and crampons while climbing on moun tains. 
Other than these, a moun taineer needs to carry lightweigh t thermal clothing , 
waterpr oof jacket, torch, first aid kit, emer gency food etc.

The Earth
Earth is the only plane t known to have life on it. It is surrounded by a layer of air 
called a tmospher e. The a tmospher e contains g ases such as o xygen, nitr ogen and 
carbon dioxide. All living things need oxygen to live. Our Earth is also called the Blue 
Plane t. This is because when astronauts first saw the Earth from space, it look ed 
blue due to the presence of water on it.out heat or light of its own. It shines because it reflects the light of the sun. Our 
Earth is a plane t.
About three-fourh t of Earth 's surface is cover ed with water and one-
fourth by land.You  Know Must (Knowledge )
Humans in Space
Human beings have always wanted to know about the mysteries of the sky. This 
motiv ated them to travel into space. Science has helped them to travel into space 
in a spacecr aft.
Yuri Gagarin was the first man to go into space on 12 April, 
1961. He was a Soviet Cosmonaut who orbit ed the Earth in 
the spacecr aft called Vostok 1.
Valen tina Tereshk ova was the first woman to go into space 
(1963).

On 21 July 1969, US astronaut Neil Arms trong became the 
first person to land on the surface of the moon. He went 
there in the spacecr aft Apollo 11.
Sunit a Williams, an Americ an astronaut of Indian origin, has 
set up world record for spending more than 50 hour s on space 
walk alone. She has spen t a total of 322 days in space.
Indians in Space
On 3rd April 1984 Squar don Leader Rakesh Sharma became the first Indian to go 
into space. He along with two Russian astronauts, went into space in a spacecr aft 
called Soyuz T-11. In his conversation with the then Prime Minis ter Mrs Indir a 
Gandhi, from space, he described India as 'Saar e Jahan Se Achcha' which means 
'The best in the world'.
It was a momen t of pride and glory for Indians. Rakesh Sharma was awarded the 
Ashok a Chakr a for his achie vemen t.
Kalpana Chawla became the first Indian woman to go into space. She went on first 
space fligh t as a part of NASA space program on 19 November 1997. In Januar y 
2003, she went on her second space mission, in the space shut tle Columbia along 
with six other astronauts. Unfortuna tely, the space shut tle exploded merely 16 
minut es before landing back on the Earth on 1 Februar y 2003.
Kalpana and all her co-astronauts died in the explosion.
The space traveller s are an inspir ation to young people who want to go into space.
The astronauts train hard to learn about space and to adap t themselv es to the 
conditions in space. The Mission Control on earth sends spacecrafts with 
astronauts into space by means of rockets.
In space s tations, ther e are separ ate modules t o work and t o live. The spacesuits 
that astronauts wear create a small atmospher e around them because there is no 
air in space.
The space shut tle carries the astronauts back to Earth after the comple tion of their 
mission. The space shut tles can be used again and again, while the rockets can only 
be used once.

Wha t is water pollution?  
Water pollution occur s when harm ful substances—oft en chemic als or micr oorganisms—c ontamina te a 
stream, river, lake, ocean, aquif er, or other body of water, degr ading water quality and rendering it toxic to 
humans or the environmen t.
The Causes of Water Pollution
Indus trial Waste. Indus tries and indus trial sites across the world are a major contribut or to water pollution.

! Agricultur al run-of fs- Use of insecticides and pesticides.

Environmental Studies-5 148Wha t is air pollution?  
Air pollution is contamina tion of the indoor or outdoor environmen t by any chemic al, physical or biologic al 
agent that modifies the natural char acteristics of the atmospher e. Household combus tion devices, motor 
vehicles, indus trial facilities and forest fires are common sour ces of air pollution.
The Causes of Air Pollution
! Air pollution can be caused by a number of factors, including: Burning fossil fuels.
! The burning of coal, oil, and natural gas for pow er in factories, electric al plan ts, and automobiles is the 
main cause of air pollution. This process releases solid particles like ash and soot, as well as harm ful 
gases. 
! The gases emit ted from cars, truck s, buses, and other vehicles pollut e the environmen t.
! Breeding farm animals can lead to poor air quality , which can negatively impact the nutrien t value of 
food. Wildfir es and volcanoes.
! Indus trial chemic als events can also cause air pollution. 
! These chemic als can also contribut e to air pollution. 
! Ozone pollution, also known as smog , is caused by the mixing of volatile organic compounds (VOCs) and 
nitrogen oxides (NOx) with sunligh t and heat. This is a common problem in the summer .
